     4. Why the numbers look this way — enumerated reasons
     The body of the section. As a \begin{enumerate} so each is
     numbered and citable. Concretely:

       a. Eio per-domain event-loop wake-up vs JVM
     LockSupport.park/unpark. Each OCaml domain runs its own
     Eio_main.run (benchmark/ocaml/bench.ml:63, 93). When
     Semaphore.release on domain A must wake an acquire parked
     on domain B, the wake-up traverses Eio's domain-safe enqueue
     → target run-queue → next scheduler poll. The JVM directly
     unparks the OS thread. This indirection is the dominant cost on
     contended single-permit primitives (Semaphore(1) W2 T=2: Java
     ≈145–211 ns, OCaml ≈9 600–11 800 ns; ratio ≈50×).
       b. java.util.concurrent.locks.ReentrantLock is reentrant; our
     Mutex is not. Java's Mutex uses
     ReentrantLock.lock/unlock, which has a state-cache fast path
     for the owning thread plus an aggressive spin-then-park loop
     under contention. SQS Mutex (implementations/mutex.ml) goes
     through the SQS suspend/resume path on every contention. The
     Mutex W2 row therefore compares apples-to-oranges; we
     acknowledge this and additionally show Semaphore(1), which is
     the closer like-for-like.
       c. Java's LinkedBlockingQueue acquires a ReentrantLock per
     put/take regardless of queue state. That's ~130–400 ns of
     lock acquire/release per op even on a hot queue. Our
     Blocking_queue_pool.put (implementations/blocking_queue_pool.ml:58–66)
     and retrieve (:78–88) are lock-free in the steady state —
     one Atomic.fetch_and_add plus one Atomic.compare_and_set /
     Atomic.exchange on a 1024-slot atomic array, no SQS
     suspend invoked. Hence the inversion: 12–22 ns vs 130–400 ns.
       d. Kotlin's Channel<T>(UNLIMITED) adds coroutine state-machine
     overhead on top of the channel buffer, on every send /
     receive. The single Kotlin row in summary.csv
     (Semaphore(1) W2 T=1, ~6.8 ns) is uncontended; under contention
     coroutine dispatch cost would compound similarly to (1).
       e. Single-permit serialisation in W2 contended. Semaphore(1)
     forces every operation through one cell of the SQS, so all
     contention in the test serialises. The added Semaphore(half)
     run (commit 3165e99, T=4 and T=8) shows that with t/2
     permits the wake-up cost is amortised across multiple parallel
     cells — confirming the bottleneck is the handoff, not the
     cell-state machine itself.
       f. Domain creation/teardown cost is included in W5 latch fire
     and W6 barrier, which create a fresh latch/barrier per cycle.
     The Java side mirrors the cycle shape (benchmark/README.md),
     so the comparison is fair, but absolute numbers in those rows
     reflect setup overhead, not steady-state primitive cost.
       g. Mean latency, not p99. Fairness should show up most clearly
     in the latency tail. We report mean only; recent commit
     8487c68 adds the mean-latency plots referenced here, but
     tail-latency analysis is left for future work.
     5. Limitations of the evaluation (~1 short paragraph)
       - Same machine, same kernel scheduler — no cross-machine variance.
       - JIT warm-up is included in 1 s warmup window; Java may still be
     mid-tier-2 compilation early in the measurement window.
       - Mean latency only.
       - Domain count = thread count: we don't isolate Eio scheduler
     overhead from raw domain-spawn overhead.

