     4. Why it's not enough — verification gaps
     The body of the limitations subsection. As an \begin{enumerate}:

       a. The 9-state SQS cell machine is not directly verified.
     lib/sqs_effects.mli is opaque — cell_state, segment,
     resume_idx, suspend_idx, and the debug helpers in
     lib/sqs_effects.ml:625–626 are not exported. Our qcheck-stm
     tests model the primitive state (permits, count); the
     cell-machine path each command exercises is only documented in
     the test headers, not asserted by postcond. Closing this gap
     requires a lib/sqs_effects_internal.ml{,i} exposing
     read_cell : 'a t → seg → int → abstract_cell_state; not in
     scope.
       b. Sync resume mode and Broken cell state are unreachable
     from production primitives. Every primitive in
     implementations/ uses ~resume_mode:Async, so the SYNC spin
     timeout (sqs_effects.ml:343) and Broken transitions are
     never exercised. They appear in lib/sqs_effects.ml but only
     in dead code from the test suite's perspective.
       c. Cancellation paths weakly covered. No qcheck-stm Cancel
     command is generated; the Waiter → Cancelling → Cancelled/Refuse paths
     (sqs_effects.ml:429,440,460–489) are exercised only via
     direct Sqs_effects.cancel_waiter calls in a couple of manual
     tests. Their interaction with concurrent ASYNC resume is
     tested only via the cancellation_mode = Smart semantics in
     the semaphore's on_cancellation callback.
       d. Time-dependent races are inherently non-deterministic. The
     Cancelling+ASYNC-resume race
     (sqs_effects.ml:395–404) and the SYNC spin timeout depend on
     hardware timing; reproducing them under qcheck-stm requires
     stress, not generation.
       e. TSAN catches data races, not deadlocks/livelocks/
     linearisation violations. A primitive that always returns
     the same wrong value but has no torn writes will not trigger
     TSAN; it would only show up under qcheck-lin/stm.
       f. macOS arm64 + TSAN setup is fragile. Required
     MallocNanoZone=0, a Clang-17 dylib symlinked into the opam
     bin directory, and a per-test -alert -deprecated workaround
     for qcheck-core's version mismatch. Any of these slipping
     silently could mean false negatives (TSAN not actually
     instrumenting). We verified instrumentation via
     otool -L .../smoke_test.exe | grep tsan (matched).
       g. qcheck-lin DSL cannot exercise blocking ops. It runs each
     command synchronously on a raw domain; acquire, await,
     retrieve are out of its scope. The lin harness fills this
     gap but is hand-rolled per primitive (~100 lines each).
       h. Mutex, Barrier, BlockingQueuePool, BlockingStackPool are
     excluded from qcheck-stm. Mutex's callback-style API
     (lock m callback rather than lock; ...; unlock) doesn't
     compose with STM's command/return shape; Barrier has only one
     command (Arrive); the pools have no useful non-blocking
     probe to compare against. Their guarantees rest on the lin
     harness + manual tests.
       i. 3-domain concurrent budget. STM_domain.arb_triple runs 3
     parallel command lists. Real multicore traffic can hit timing
     windows that 3 domains never cover; we mitigate with 200 ×
     retries=10 per Test.make, but it remains a finite cover.
       j. Sample size. 1000 sequential + 200 concurrent runs per
     primitive is bounded; rare interleavings (probability < 1/200
     per linearisation) won't be hit consistently.
