 This is a pure implementation task. We are on branch sync_test_suite,
 forked clean from implementation (no divergence yet, working tree
 clean). The branch is local-only — no origin/sync_test_suite exists,
 so we choose when to first push.

 The change in two sentences. Every primitive in implementations/
 currently configures its SQS with ~resume_mode:Async and writes
 ignore (resume t.sqs ...) because Async never fails. Sync mode can
 fail (the spin times out, the cell becomes Broken, resume returns
 false, and the value is dropped silently —
 lib/sqs_effects.ml:336-352, max_spin_cycles = 100 at line 213).
 Switching a primitive to Sync therefore requires explicit retry or
 salvage logic on every resume call site, otherwise permits/values
 leak and waiters deadlock.

 Kotlin precedent. Only SyncSemaphoreSmart
 (test/CqsLincheck.kt:141-194) is built in Sync mode in the Kotlin
 reference; Mutex, CountDownLatch, Barrier, and the pools are all Async
 even there. The pattern Kotlin uses for Sync semaphore: retry loop
 around resume in release, manual cont.resume(false) in acquire
 to trigger an outer retry, and a returnValue callback that
 re-releases a refused permit. Lincheck for that class disables the
 obstruction-freedom check
 (test/CqsLincheck.kt:226-231) because Sync-mode spinning can block.

 Task 10 says "all primitives", so this plan covers all six even though
 Kotlin only ships one. The non-trivial ones (CountDownLatch, Barrier)
 get explicit design choices captured below.

 Approach

 Naming and file organisation

 Add new files alongside the existing Async ones rather than mutating
 them. Naming: <primitive>_sync.ml (and .mli where the existing
 primitive has one — none currently do). Module name follows OCaml's
 file-derived convention: Semaphore_sync, Mutex_sync,
 Count_down_latch_sync, Barrier_sync, Blocking_queue_pool_sync,
 Blocking_stack_pool_sync.

 This keeps the Async versions byte-for-byte identical (no risk of
 regressing prior tests/benchmarks) and lets the test harnesses
 exercise both side-by-side.

 Per-primitive implementation

 Each Sync primitive follows the same shape as its Async counterpart
 but adds three things on every resume callsite: (a) a retry loop
 that re-attempts resume until it returns true, (b) a
 return_value callback wired into Sqs_effects.make so values
 landing on Refuse cells flow back into the primitive's state, and
 (c) for acquire/await-style operations, a manual fail-and-retry
 loop in case suspend was discontinued by a SYNC race.

 Concrete per-primitive deltas (all paths relative to repo root):

 1. implementations/semaphore_sync.ml — direct port of Kotlin's
 SyncSemaphoreSmart (test/CqsLincheck.kt:141-194).
   - make: Sqs_effects.make ~resume_mode:Sync ~cancellation_mode:Smart ~on_cancellation:... ~return_value:(fun () -> release t). The
 return_value callback re-releases the permit when a Sync
 resume is refused.
   - release: wrap the existing if p < 0 then resume t.sqs () in a
 while not (resume t.sqs ()) do ... done retry. The retry first
 re-increments permits (matching Kotlin's pattern at lines
 169-179) so each iteration is a fresh permit/release pair.
   - acquire: same FAA fast path; on the slow path, if suspend
 returns via the cancelled-because-Broken route, retry the whole
 acquire from the top.
 2. implementations/mutex_sync.ml — adapted from
 implementations/mutex.ml plus the Sync semaphore retry pattern.
 lock's callback-style API stays the same;unlock becomes a
 while not (resume m.sqs ()) do ... done loop, with return_value
 set to a no-op since refused unlocks have no payload to recycle
 (mutex doesn't carry a counter to put back into).
 3. implementations/count_down_latch_sync.ml — the multi-resume
 case (for _ = 1 to w do ignore (resume t.sqs ()) done becomes a
 per-waiter retry loop). Design choice: when count drops to zero,
 resume_waiters must successfully wake each registered waiter, so
 each resume call is wrapped while not (resume t.sqs ()) do ... done individually. Without this, a single Broken cell would leave
 that waiter parked forever. return_value is a no-op (the latch
 carries unit values).
 4. implementations/barrier_sync.ml — same shape as the Sync
 latch: the last-arriving party loops parties - 1 resumes, each
 wrapped in its own retry. return_value is a no-op.
 5. implementations/blocking_queue_pool_sync.ml — value-bearing.
 The Async version already has a retry at
 implementations/blocking_queue_pool.ml:62
 (if not (resume t.sqs element) then put t element). The Sync
 version uses the same retry but with return_value set to deposit
 the refused element into the slot array via try_insert, so a
 refused value is salvaged rather than re-attempted via resume.
 6. implementations/blocking_stack_pool_sync.ml — same as the
 Sync queue pool but using the Treiber-stack backing of
 blocking_stack_pool.ml.

