 Risks / design notes worth surfacing

     - Multi-resume primitives under Sync are a stretch. Latch and
     Barrier each issue $N-1$ or $N$ resume calls in a tight loop. Per
     the SQS contract, Sync resume busy-spins for 100 cycles per call.
     Worst case is a barrier with $N$ parties on $N$ cancelled cells:
     the last-arriver spins $N \times 100$ cycles. This is a deliberate
     semantic choice and matches the Sync contract; it is also why
     Kotlin chose not to ship Sync variants of these. We will document
     the cost in the file headers.
     - The return_value callback only fires on REFUSE cells, not on
     BROKEN cells. A timeout that produces Broken truly drops the
     value; only the cancellation-mode = Smart path with a refused cell
     routes through return_value. This means our retry loops cannot
     assume return_value will catch every dropped value — they must
     check the bool return of resume and act on it directly. This is
     the structural reason the Async ignore (resume ...) pattern is
     unsafe in Sync mode.
     - Lincheck obstruction-freedom check. Per Kotlin's
     SyncSemaphoreSmart1LincheckTest, the OF check should be disabled
     for Sync primitives because spinning is non-obstruction-free.
     qcheck-stm has no equivalent flag, so we just note it in the test
     file header.

